               <p>2233. <persName id="def1-2233-18480918" type="defendantName">
                     <interp inst="def1-2233-18480918" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                     <interp inst="def1-2233-18480918" type="age" value="20"></interp>
                     <interp inst="def1-2233-18480918" type="surname" value="REBURN"></interp>
                     <interp inst="def1-2233-18480918" type="given" value="CHARLES"></interp>
                     <hi rend="largeCaps">CHARLES REBURN</hi>
                  </persName>
                  <rs id="t18480918-2233-offence-1" type="offenceDescription">
                     <interp inst="t18480918-2233-offence-1" type="offenceCategory" value="deception"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18480918-2233-offence-1" type="offenceSubcategory" value="forgery"></interp>, feloniously and knowingly uttering a forged order for the payment of 2<hi rend="italic">l</hi>. 15<hi rend="italic">s</hi>., with intent to defraud <persName id="t18480918-name-1017" type="victimName">
                        <interp inst="t18480918-name-1017" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18480918-name-1017" type="surname" value="ROSE"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18480918-name-1017" type="given" value="ISAAC"></interp>
                        <join result="offenceVictim" targOrder="Y" targets="t18480918-2233-offence-1 t18480918-name-1017"></join>Isaac Rose</persName>.</rs>
               </p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">MR. ROBINSON</hi> 
                  <hi rend="italic">conducted the Prosecution.</hi>
               </p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">
                     <persName id="t18480918-name-1018" type="witnessName">
                        <interp inst="t18480918-name-1018" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18480918-name-1018" type="surname" value="TIMOTHY"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18480918-name-1018" type="given" value="JOHN"></interp>JOHN TIMOTHY</persName>
                  </hi>. I am an upholsterer, of Tooley-street. On 22nd Aug. I was in a public-house, about eleven o'clock in the morning—I saw the pri<lb></lb>soner, with a pen and ink in his hand—he stated he was going to Quebec, as steward in a ship, and that he had an advance-note that he wanted to get cashed, and he would give any one 6<hi rend="italic">s</hi>. if they would tell him where he could get it cashed—he bought a mattress and palliasse of me for 6<hi rend="italic">s</hi>.—I then took him to Mr. Rose.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="italic">Cross-examined by</hi> 
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">MR. CHARNOCK</hi>. <hi rend="italic">Q.</hi> How came you to take him to Mr. Rose? <hi rend="italic">A.</hi> He said he wanted some things, and he wanted his note cashed—he said he would pay me when he got it cashed.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">
                     <persName id="t18480918-name-1019" type="witnessName">
                        <interp inst="t18480918-name-1019" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18480918-name-1019" type="surname" value="ROSE"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18480918-name-1019" type="given" value="ISAAC"></interp>ISAAC ROSE</persName>
                  </hi>. I am a clothier in Tooley-street. On 22nd Aug. the pri<lb></lb>soner came to my shop—he produced this note and said he wished it cashed he said he was steward of the <hi rend="italic">Wallace</hi> barque, going to Quebec—he said</p>
               <xptr type="pageFacsimile" doc="184809180192"></xptr>
               <p>he would take part in clothes—he looked out clothes to the amount of 2<hi rend="italic">l</hi>. 1<hi rend="italic">s</hi>. 6<hi rend="italic">d</hi>., and I gave him 13<hi rend="italic">s</hi>. 6<hi rend="italic">d</hi>.—it was raining at the time, and he took a cap and an umbrella, and the other things were to be sent to the Docks—they were sent and they came back, there was no such vessel—the prisoner wrote the name of Charles Reed on the back of the order—when these orders are passed it is customary for the person to write his own name on them.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">
                     <persName id="t18480918-name-1020" type="witnessName">
                        <interp inst="t18480918-name-1020" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18480918-name-1020" type="surname" value="BROWN"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18480918-name-1020" type="given" value="JOHN WILLIAM"></interp>JOHN WILLIAM BROWN</persName>
                  </hi>. I am clerk to Messrs. Steinback and Son, they are brokers to the ship <hi rend="italic">Wallace</hi>, Captain Robert Morton—she sailed on the 19th Aug.—I have a list of the seaman, returned to us by the captain from the Downs—we chartered the vessel—the name of Reed or Reburn does not appear in this list—we should not pay any money on this paper—I do not know Mr. Robert Forbes—I have not made inquiry for him.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="italic">Cross-examined. Q.</hi> May there not be another ship called <hi rend="italic">Wallace</hi>? <hi rend="italic">A.</hi> There may, I believe there are many—I dare say there are many Mortons—men sometimes join the ship at Gravesend after it is cleared out—this paper is brought up by the pilot who leaves the ship in the Downs—if a man joins the ship after the pilot leaves, we should not have the account in this paper, but if the man has an advance-note we should have an account from the cap<lb></lb>tain.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">MR. ROBINSON</hi>. <hi rend="italic">Q.</hi> When did the ship sail? <hi rend="italic">A.</hi> She cleared out at the Customs on 19th Aug., and went down to Gravesend the same day.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">
                     <persName id="t18480918-name-1021" type="witnessName">
                        <interp inst="t18480918-name-1021" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18480918-name-1021" type="surname" value="DATE"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18480918-name-1021" type="given" value="JOSEPH"></interp>JOSEPH DATE</persName>
                  </hi>. I am a clerk in the Register Office for Seamen. I pro<lb></lb>duce the official list of the crew on board the <hi rend="italic">Wallace</hi> of Glasgow, which sailed for Quebec—this list is deposited by the captain, and signed by him on the completion of his crew—this is signed just before the vessel goes—it is made evidence by the Act of Parliament—the name of Reid or Reburn is not here—there may be many vessels named <hi rend="italic">Wallace</hi>, but they would not agree with this in the tonnage, the day of sailing, and the captain's name—I have made inquiries respecting these facts from public books, and from those in<lb></lb>quiries I can undertake to say that there was no other <hi rend="italic">Wallace</hi>, Captain Mor<lb></lb>ton, sailed for Quebec on that day—this note bears the name of Reburn—I had an official counterpart of the same—it bears a number which is supposed to be the number of the prisoner's register-ticket—it is 74360—I have ascertained that the name of the person to whom No. 74360 is applicable, is Thorns Lacey.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">EVAN-JONES</hi> (<hi rend="italic">policeman, M</hi> 250). I took the prisoner—I told him the charge—he said nothing then—he afterwards said we ought to take the other man he received that note from—I took from him this seaman's ticket, with the name of Reburn on it—I read the name of Charles Reburn—he said, "That is my name; that is my ticket."</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">
                     <rs id="t18480918-2233-verdict-1" type="verdictDescription">
